Question: If the Governing Council objects to a draft supervisory decision under
  the non-objection procedure, what avenues exist to resolve the
  disagreement, and how is the Mediation Panel composed?
Example answer: If the Governing Council objects, three procedures may be followed: an
  NCA concerned by the decision and with different views may request
  mediation; if no request for mediation is submitted, the Supervisory
  Board may amend the draft decision in order to incorporate the
  comments of the Governing Council; or, if the Supervisory Board does
  not submit a new draft decision, the objections are sent to the
  responsible business areas. The Mediation Panel includes one member
  per participating Member State, chosen from among the members of the
  Governing Council and the Supervisory Board, and decides by simple
  majority with each member having one vote. (ECB Supervisory Manual,
  pages 17, 24)
Predicted answer: Avenues to resolve a Governing Council objection under the
  non‑objection procedure - Mediation request by the concerned NCA: an
  NCA may request mediation so that the objection is dealt with by the
  Mediation Panel.   - Supervisory Board amendment: if no mediation is
  requested, the Supervisory Board may amend the draft decision to
  incorporate the Governing Council’s comments.   - Referral back to
  business areas: if the Supervisory Board does not submit a new
  draft, the objections are sent back to the responsible business
  areas.  Relevant timelines (as given) - Governing Council
  non‑objection period: up to ten working days for the Governing
