  supervision separate to avoid conflicts of interest and to ensure
  “each function is exercised in accordance with its applicable
  objectives.” (ECB Supervisory Manual, p. 8; the Manual cites SSMR
  Article 25 and ECB Decision ECB/2014/39 as the legal basis.) - How
  at Governing Council level: supervisory decisions are prepared and
  approved inside the ECB by the independent Supervisory Board and
  submitted to the Governing Council under a non‑objection procedure —
  the Governing Council “may adopt or object to the proposed decisions
  but cannot in principle modify them.” (ECB Supervisory Manual, pp.
  8, 16). Procedural safeguards keep supervisory deliberations
  separate from other ECB business, limit information flows, and
  require Executive Board approval for certain confidential transfers.
  (ECB Supervisory Manual, p. 8.)  Key points and supporting extracts
